# .herd/triggers.tsv — declarative SCHEDULED / TRIGGERED RUNS (HERD-169). Commit this (code-shaped
# config, zero-secret). A cron-style trigger spawns a defined workflow (a named backlog-item template
# or a steps.tsv pipeline — whatever the task text names) on schedule by ENQUEUEING spawn intents onto
# the SAME durable spawn queue the coordinator uses (scripts/herd/spawn.sh). It never bypasses a gate:
# every spawned intent runs the normal builder → healthcheck → review → merge pipeline.
#
# Format — one TAB-SEPARATED row per trigger (columns separated by a literal tab, NOT spaces):
#     name <TAB> schedule <TAB> lane <TAB> task <TAB> input
#
#   name      kebab-ish label; the snapshot key, the journal key, and the spawn slug prefix.
#   schedule  the cadence a tick fires this trigger on — one of:
#               @hourly | @daily | @weekly | every:<N>[smhd] (e.g. every:30m, every:6h, every:2d) | manual
#             'manual' NEVER auto-fires on a tick; fire it explicitly with 'triggers.sh fire <name>'.
#   lane      quick | feature — the durable-queue lane each spawned intent runs in.
#   task      the task text handed to each spawned builder (its "workflow"). Tokens substituted PER
#             spawn:  {item} → the delta input line that triggered it · {name} → the trigger name.
#   input     a shell command whose STDOUT lines are the INPUT SET (one item per line). Each fire diffs
#             this set against the previous run's snapshot and spawns work ONLY for the DELTA (new
#             lines). An empty input set spawns nothing.
#
# ── DIFF-AGAINST-LAST-RUN ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# A per-trigger last-run input snapshot is stored under .herd/trigger-state/<name>.snapshot (runtime
# state; gitignored). On each fire:
#   • FIRST RUN (no snapshot) ⇒ FULL RUN: every line spawns, loudly labelled.
#   • UNCHANGED input          ⇒ no delta ⇒ nothing spawns.
#   • CHANGED input            ⇒ only the added lines spawn.
# FAIL-SOFT: if the input command errors, nothing spawns, the snapshot is kept, and the next tick
# retries. Validate with:
#     bash scripts/herd/triggers.sh validate
#
# The tick CADENCE is external (an operator cron or scheduler runs 'triggers.sh tick'); the schedule
# column decides which triggers are DUE when a tick lands. Fire one now with 'triggers.sh fire <name>'.
#
# HARD RULE: an EMPTY or ABSENT list ⇒ a byte-identical engine (this feature ships DORMANT / default-off).
# Blank lines and lines whose first field starts with '#' are ignored.
#
# ── Examples (all commented out; uncomment + adapt) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Nightly: open a quick fix for each file flagged by a linter that wasn't flagged yesterday.
# lint-sweep<TAB>@daily<TAB>quick<TAB>Fix the lint finding in {item} and open a PR.<TAB>scripts/lint.sh --list-files
#
# Hourly: spawn a feature build for each new open issue label since the last run.
# issue-triage<TAB>@hourly<TAB>feature<TAB>Triage and address issue {item} (see the issue-triage backlog template).<TAB>gh issue list --label ready --json number -q '.[].number'
#
# Manual: re-run the release-notes pipeline on demand (never auto-fires).
# release-notes<TAB>manual<TAB>quick<TAB>Regenerate release notes for {item}.<TAB>git tag --points-at HEAD
